2598,"Wenban-Smith, H. et al.",2016,Food security in Tanzania: the challenge of rapid urbanization,Academic-peer reviewed,Tanzania,National,,,1.4,2.3,1,2,+2: Reinforcing,2,Positive,"future urban food security may depend to a large extent on raising production and productivity in the smallholder rural farming sector, and raising participation of these farmers in food supply chains. However, rural smallholder food production is already constrained by the pressure of population on land and other resources, while subsistence requirements, inadequate support services and poor market access limit their market participation.","To overcome these challenges, Tanzanian policy is already shifting from the goal of supplying urban populations with food at favourable prices to a more rural focus with the aim of improving the capacity of rural areas to meet growing urban demand.  Kilimo Kwanza: is a national strategy of the Government which includes increasing crop production, improving livestock husbandry and undertaking fish farming.   'The goal of supplying the urban population with food at favourable prices was frequently pursued both with agricultural and trade policy, and with income policy and selective support measures' despite empirical evidence that 'poverty and food insecurity are to be found primarily in rural areas of Africa' (Geier 1995, p.167). Twenty years later, the Tanzanian Government still struggles to balance the competing objectives of ensuring adequate prices to producers while maintaining low prices for consumers (Temu et al. 2010; Haug and Hella 2013).",,,,Strong,"Urban population growth and projections for Tanzania see Tables 1 and 2 (p. 975)  The Tanzanian Ministry of Agriculture, Food Security and Cooperatives highlights that food security in urban areas is mainly threatened by increasing food prices and higher price fluctuations compared to rural areas (URT 2006). This is also underlined by theWorld Food Programme, where main causes of urban food shortages in Tanzania are attributed to Bno money^ (35 %), Bdrought^ (15 %) and Bexpensive food^ (18 %) (WFP 2013). WFP also notes that urban households source their food mainly frompurchasing (Dar es Salaam 97% and other urban areas 77 %), while rural households derive on average 58 % of their food supply from own resources; and WFP finds that periods of food shortages are on average higher in urban regions (4 months) and Dar es Salaam (4.2 months) compared to rural regions (3.4 months).","We suggest that future policy needs to reinforce these efforts by further promotion of rural development, putting more resources into initiatives such as Kilimo Kwanza. This is a national strategy of the Government which includes increasing crop production, improving livestock husbandry and undertaking fish farming. Furthermore, rural–urban linkages would benefit from a sustained program to strengthen value chains, particularly as regards storage, processing, transport and marketing of agricultural products. Public-Private Partnership Projects like the Southern Agricultural Growth Corridor may point the way. Research could further explore the potential of market gardening in peri-urban areas. Finally, considering the demand-side, increased awareness and education about food safety and food quality would help to contribute to food security in the process of urbanization.",,Paper's focus is on urban food security in Tanzania,983
